defaultAbleChildAfrica commends the positive work being done by DFID through its twin-track approach to disability. It is a leader in promoting t
defaulthe rights 
defaultand 
defaultinclusion of disabled people in development and putting the issue of disability on the global agenda. Its ‘Disability, Poverty and Development’ issues paper, 
defaultg
defaultuidance note and other disability practice papers comprehensively detail what needs
default to be done to ensure that disability is no longer side lined.  
default2.1.2.
default 
default While this high level support is evident, there is still a noticeable gap between the sentiments of the papers and what is actually being practiced on the ground. For instance, despite the 2
default007 practice paper on ‘Working on Disability in Country Programmes’, a 
default2011 
defaultreport highlighted the significant absence of written statements in DFID country operational plans to reduce educational marginalisation for any vulnerable group other than girls
default.
default 
defaultUnless these papers are elevated to policies and implementation monitored, we fear there will be little change in practices, particularly with regard to 
defaultmainstreaming.
default2.1.3.
default 
default We recommend that a policy 
defaultthat draws together and builds on these existing documents 
defaultand DFID’s twin-track approach 
defaultis developed, implemented, and 
defaultresourced
default with a realistic and practical monitoring and accountability fra
defaultmework.
