default2.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDisability mainstreaming within DFID’s sector programmes
default2.2.1.
default 
default DFID’s recognition that the MDGs cannot be achieved without addressing disability is an important statement that highlights the necessity of disability mainstreaming. As an effective tool for bridging the equity gap, we hope to see DFID continue and stren
defaultgthen its efforts to incorporate disability mainstreaming practices across its sector programmes.
default2.2.2.
default 
default Currently there is still room for improvement to be made by DFID, particularly within core sectors - such as health and education - that impact the lives of 
defaultdisabled people. For example, although over 20% of the UK aid budget for this financial year has been allocated to health
default, we continue to observe many difficulties faced by disabled children and their families in accessing and receiving health services, a
defaultt disproportionate levels to others. In fact, a recent study by Plan International found that
default 
defaultdisabled children
default are significantly more likely to have had a serious illness, including malnutrition than 
defaulttheir non-disabled peers
default. In the areas where we work, 
defaultthis pattern was observed most strongly for children with intellectual impairments. 
default2.2.3.
default 
default Within the education sector, DFID has s
defaultupport
defaulted
default developing countries
default’
default 
defaultwork towards achieving the MDG
default of 
defaultuniversal primary education
default (UPE), unfortunately research demonstr
defaultates this progress has actually increased disparities faced by disabled children. P
defaultolitically reverberant pressure to meet 
defaultMDG/UPE
default deadlines has contributed to increasingly overcrowded classes, insufficiently trained teachers and dec
defaultlining quality; 
defaultefforts
default to meet 
defaultUPE
default 
defaultthen 
defaultmay 
defaultironically be 
defaulthindering the 
defaultconditions necessary for 
defaultthe inclusion of disabled children, without whom the goal cannot ultimately to be 
defaultrealis
defaulted.
default We endorse the comprehensive 2010 DFID practice paper ‘Education for Children with Disabi
defaultlities – Improving access and quality’. Yet as with the health sector, there is still much
default to be done on transforming this 
defaultguidance notes into institutionalised practices and approaches. 
default2.2.3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAlmost ¾ of out of school children are in sub-Saharan Africa and dis
defaultabled children are disproportionately represented in this group
default.  In fact, up to 98% of disabled children in developing countries do not attend school (UNICEF). The 
defaultWorld Report on Disability
default reaffirms the finding that disabled children are less likely to
default attend school and demonstrates the adverse impact this has on human capital formation, employment, future earnings and productivity in adulthood
default.  
default2.2.3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEvidence shows that whilst 63% of African children finish primary school, only 2% of disabled children 
defaultreach this stage
default. 
defaultIn 
defaultTanzania where we work, being disabled doubles the probability that a child will never attend school
default.  M
defaultaking effective use of DFID’s practice paper on education, 
defaultcould result in a 
defaultsignificant positive shift in 
defaultthese
default figure
defaults
default.
default2.2.4.
default 
default To hel
defaultp enhance its mainstreaming efforts, we also recommend that DFID utilises
default 
defaultdisability-disaggregated data and indicators. Guidance should also be available on how to plan for and gather accurate data. AbleChildAfrica is aware that many disabled children lack
default access to protection, medical, psychosocial and legal services (UNICEF, 2005)
default 
defaultso it is particularly important to ensure that data 
defaults
defaulturrounding these 
defaultissues 
