default2.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDFID’s approach to rehabilitation an
defaultd service provision for disabled people
default2.3.1.
default 
default DFID’s practice papers rightly identify and emphasise that both mainstream and disability specific services 
defaultshould be
default holistic in their delivery. We call on DFID to ensure that both tracks are addressed simultaneous
defaultly in a coordinated way. Furthermore, early interventions can reduce the likelihood of intersecting issues compounding upon on
defaulte another.  O
defaultur partners 
defaultoften tell us 
defaultthat poor access to health care, habilitation and rehabilitation services impacts on the ac
defaultcessibility of education and skills training for disabled children and young people. 
default2.3.2.
default 
default As a signatory of the UN Convention on the Right
defaults of Persons with Disabilities
default, the UK
default government supports the right to the provision of learning materials, sign languag
defaulte and other assistive technologies. 
defaultWe
default would
default therefore call upon DFID to ensure that
default a
defaultssistive aids
default that support a disabled child’s development and functionality 
defaultare
default considered an essential service provision across all projects. While doing so, it is impor
defaulttant to avoid stockpiling of unwanted or unsuitable devices, so there should be flexibility in the procurement requirements for such items to ensure that actual individual needs on the ground are being met. 
default2.3.3.
default 
default Of particu
defaultlar concern to AbleChildAfrica
default, are t
defaulthe unmet needs of children with 
defaultlearning disabilities or 
defaultintellectual impairments and 
defaultthose
default with complex impairments
default, as well as
default their families. Entrenched stigma and social isolation unfortunately mean that actual prevalence will remain underreported unti
defaultl data collection and reporting are improved, however we know from our partners that the ability of families to access quality, or any, services remains a challenge. We believe there is an opportunity for DFID to be a leader in addressing this gap and sett
defaulting the model for good practice using its rights-based approach. 
default2.3.4.
default 
default Finally, we recommend that the indicators used to measure success in the fields of rehabilitation and service provision go beyond tangible outputs and short term results
default to measure the real impact on individual lives. For example, a child who receives a wheelchair may not necessarily be able to access their local school or other community facilities and therefore continues to face barriers to inclusion. Such data should b
defaulte captured across mainstream as well as disability-specific programmes.
