default2.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRole of disabled people in DFID’s policy and programmes
default2.5.1.
default 
default In recent years we have seen positive steps taken by DFID to ensure that disabled people have a bigger role and more voice within its work. Of p
defaultarticular note is the collaboration with disabl
defaulted person’s organisations
default 
default(DPOs) 
defaultto undertake 
defaultaccessibility audits of DFID offices as well as steps taken
default to receive direct feedback from project beneficiaries. However, there is little evidence of DFID direct
defaultly listening to the voices of disabled 
defaultchildren
default or their families and we call upon DFID to extend their consultative practice to this group as well.
default2.5.2.
default 
default AbleChildAfrica is however, concerned that disabled people, particularly children, still remain mainly rec
defaultipients of aid rather than leaders and implementers of the process. It is our belief that disabled people of all ages must play a central role in all stages of policy and programme development as well as implementation. 
defaultWithin Africa
default there are cultural con
defaultstraints on the role of a child and their visibility is less pronounced. Combined with the added marginalisation of being disabled, it is important to safeguard the voices and opinions of disabled children
default 
defaultin addition to promoting their access to services, social participation, inclusive play and protection. For empowerment and advocacy outcomes in particular, which can be harder to measure, we strongly recommend engaging with disabled children and y
defaultouth, as
default well as their families, 
defaultto determine what they consider to be indicators of success within such programmes. 
default2.5.3.
default 
defaultDisabled girls in particular are known to face more barriers than boys,
default 
defaultespecially in 
defaultsocieties 
defaultthat 
defaultfavour males to females
default. This makes them less
default likely to obtain health care, get an education, receive vocational training or find employment
default. On top of this, women and girls with disabilities are more 
defaultlikely to experience
default practices which qualify as torture or inhuman or degrading treatment and are m
defaultore susceptible to violence and abuse
default. The 
defaultmultiple 
defaultdiscrimination and additional marginalisation 
defaultdisabled girls
default face 
defaultresults in poorer access to services and silenced voices 
defaultwithin the development auditorium.
default&#xa0;
default2.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFinancial costs and benefits of 
defaultan increased
default emphasis on disability
default2.6.1.
default 
defaultDFID’s Disability, Poverty and Dev
defaultelopment paper states that disability is a cause and consequence of poverty. 
defaultEmpowerment of disabled people to break out of the chronic poverty cycle requires directed efforts to ensure their access
default to services and inclusion in the society; 
defaultgiving consideration to disability issues and investing accordingly directly contributes to reducing poverty.  We recommend DFID adopt a policy of introducing an accessibility budget line into all programme funds 
defaultin support of this goal. “Poverty reduction cannot be met without considering the needs of disabled people.”
default 
default2.6.2.
default 
defaultWe welcome DFID’s recent announcement to 
defaultonly 
defaultsupport the construction of accessible schools and hope to see a comprehensive approach of inclusiv
defaulte design applied. It will be important that guidelines on accessibility, as well as training on these guidelines
default,
default are rolled 
defaultout. We would like to encourage DFID to continue in this vein with all infrastructure project
default,
defaults especially since 
defaultthe 
defaultWorld Bank est
defaultimates that 
defaultaccessibility cost
defaults
default are generally less than 1% of total construction costs
default. 
default2.6.3.
default 
default Investing in early childhood development is also an important way of not only engaging with the issue of inclusion, but also increasing the chances of detecting and 
defaultpreventing health issues that can lead to lifelong impairments. Being excluded from early childhood education significantly reduces the opportunities that disabled children can have later in life in terms of securing wor
defaultking and financial stability. 
defaultResear
defaultch demonstrates that an individual’s potential income can increase by as much as 10% with each additional year of schooling
default, and this figure is likely to be even greater for disabled people, whose baseline earnings are undoubtedly significantly lower. Fur
defaultthermore
default this increased independency will 
defaultreduce the financial 
defaultresponsibility
default that is often
default placed on
default family members and government funds.
